  "prompt": "What can I do if SharePoint alerts aren't working?",
  "response": "SharePoint alerts not working can be frustrating. Here's a comprehensive troubleshooting guide to help you diagnose and fix the issue:\n\n**1. Basic Checks:**\n\n*   **Check Your Email:**  Sounds obvious, but confirm you're checking the correct email address and that alerts aren't going to your spam or junk folder. Add SharePoint email addresses (usually something like `noreply@sharepointonline.com`) to your safe senders list.\n*   **Alerts Are Enabled:**\n    *   **For the List/Library:**  Go to the List/Library Settings > Alert Settings.  Make sure alerts are generally enabled for that list or library.  (Sometimes someone might have disabled them globally).\n    *   **For Your User:**  See if you accidentally disabled alerts in your personal settings (see section 3).\n*   **Permissions:**  You need at least \"Read\" permissions on the list/library and the specific item(s) you're trying to receive alerts for.\n*   **Recent Changes:**  Has anything changed recently?  Did someone update the list/library settings, change your permissions, or modify the alert rules?  Knowing what changed can help pinpoint the problem.\n*   **System-Wide Outage:**  Check the Microsoft 365 service health dashboard to see if there's a known outage affecting SharePoint Online.\n\n**2. Verify Your Alert Settings:**\n\n*   **Access Your Alert Settings (SharePoint Online/Modern):**\n    1.  Go to the List or Library where you expect alerts.\n    2.  Click the ellipsis (three dots) `...` in the command bar.\n    3.  Click `Alert me`.  This may say `Manage my alerts` if you already have alerts set up.\n    4.  Alternatively, go to a specific item and click the ellipsis.\n*   **Review These Settings:**\n    *   **Alert Title:**  Meaningful titles help you identify the alert.\n    *   **Send Alerts To:**  Double-check the email address is correct.  If you're part of a group, ensure the group is configured to receive emails (a common mistake).\n    *   **Change Type:**\n        *   `All changes`:  Alerts on any change.\n        *   `New items are added`:  Only alerts when a new item is created.\n        *   `Existing items are modified`: Only alerts when an item is changed.\n        *   `Items are deleted`: Only alerts when an item is deleted.\n    *   **Send Alerts For These Changes:**\n        *   `Anyone changes an item`:  Alerts for any change by anyone.\n        *   `Someone changes an item that I created`: Alerts only when someone changes an item you created.\n        *   `Someone changes an item that I last modified`: Alerts only when someone changes an item you last modified.\n    *   **When To Send Alerts:**\n        *   `Send email immediately`: Alerts are sent as soon as the change occurs (subject to processing time).\n        *   `Send a daily summary`:  A summary of changes is sent once a day.  Check the \"Send Daily Summary At\" time.\n        *   `Send a weekly summary`: A summary of changes is sent once a week.  Check the \"Send Weekly Summary On\" day.\n*   **Test with a Specific Change:** Create a new item or modify an existing one that matches your alert criteria.  Then, wait a reasonable amount of time (a few minutes for immediate alerts, up to 24 hours for daily summaries).\n\n**3. Check User Profile Settings:**\n\n*   **Navigate to your User Profile:** In SharePoint Online, typically you can click on your profile picture in the upper-right corner, then \"My Microsoft Account\" or \"View Account\", then find a link to \"Profile\".  The exact path may vary based on your organization's setup.\n*   **Check Notification Preferences:** Look for settings related to email notifications.  Ensure that notifications from SharePoint are enabled.  This is less common, but it's worth checking.\n\n**4. Advanced Troubleshooting:**\n\n*   **Complex Alert Rules:** If you're using calculated columns or complex formulas in your alert logic, those might be causing issues. Simplify the rules to test.\n*   **Workflows:** If workflows are modifying items, the alerts might be triggered by the workflow, not the user. Check the workflow's settings to ensure it's not interfering with alerts.  Consider logging within the workflow to confirm it's running correctly and when.\n*   **Regional Settings:**  In older versions of SharePoint, incorrect regional settings (date/time formats) could sometimes interfere with alerts. Verify your regional settings are correct.\n*   **Large Lists/Libraries:** Very large lists/libraries (especially with many alerts) can sometimes cause performance issues. Consider breaking the list into smaller lists or using metadata and views to filter data.\n*   **Third-Party Apps:** If you're using any third-party apps or add-ins related to SharePoint, they could be interfering with alerts. Try disabling them temporarily to see if that resolves the issue.\n*   **Power Automate (Microsoft Flow):** Consider using Power Automate (Microsoft Flow) to create custom notification workflows.  This offers more flexibility and control over when and how alerts are sent.\n\n**5. Server-Side Considerations (More relevant for on-premises SharePoint):**\n\n*   **Timer Jobs:** SharePoint uses timer jobs to process alerts.  Ensure the \"Immediate Alerts\" and \"Daily/Weekly Alerts\" timer jobs are running correctly.  You'll need SharePoint Administrator access to check this in Central Administration.\n*   **SMTP Settings:** Ensure your SharePoint server is correctly configured to send emails via SMTP.  Test the SMTP connection.\n*   **Event Viewer:** Check the SharePoint server's Event Viewer for any errors related to alerts or email delivery.\n*   **Uptime:** Verify the server running SharePoint is up and running and not experiencing performance issues.\n\n**6. Contact Support:**\n\n*   If you've tried all of these steps and alerts are still not working, contact your organization's IT support or SharePoint administrator. They may have access to server-side logs and configurations that can help diagnose the problem. If you are an administrator and none of these steps work, contact Microsoft support.\n\n**Steps to Take When Asking for Help (IT Support or Online Forums):**\n\nWhen asking for help, provide as much detail as possible:\n\n*   **SharePoint Version:**  Are you using SharePoint Online, SharePoint Server 2019, 2016, etc.?\n*   **Specific List/Library:** Which list or library is affected?\n*   **Detailed Alert Settings:** Copy and paste your alert settings (without revealing sensitive information, of course).\n*   **Steps You've Already Tried:** List the troubleshooting steps you've already taken.\n*   **Error Messages:** Include any error messages you've seen.\n*   **Expected vs. Actual Behavior:** Clearly describe what you expect to happen and what is actually happening.\n*   **User Affected:** Is the issue only affecting one user or multiple users?\n\nBy following these steps, you should be able to identify and resolve most common SharePoint alert issues. Remember to test thoroughly after making any changes.\n",
